    "if an intent comes through one of my prompts that already has been worded in close enough words before … a properly behaving agent would not just add more, just add another entry. But I wonder, well, I don't wonder, there's a problem with that, which is that now the timestamp isn't really reflecting how recent that intent is."
    "Identifying the restatement-handling problem. The skill already says don't duplicate (`skills/intent-log.md` §'Recording protocol' tells agents to query priors before adding; supersession protocol for contradictions). The gap: pure reaffirmation (no contradiction; just psyche repeating themselves) isn't covered."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:00:00Z)

(Correction
    "Chat output discipline: no `---` horizontal-rule separators, no labeled-field structures (no 'Mechanism: …' / 'Example: …' headers, no rendered tables with field-name chips). The user reads dense inline prose better than bureaucratic scaffolding; labeled fields and visual dividers feel like being talked-down-to. The no-`---` rule already in AGENTS.md for markdown files extends to chat output. The NOTA-design principle (no labeled fields; the position is the schema) applies to chat prose too: state the option, state its tradeoff, state the lean — inline, no scaffolding."
    "This is exactly the formatting style that I dislike. --- separator lines, named fields (mechanism, example) which I did away with my NOTA format. Everything about this way of presenting is 'lots of noise'. My mind repels from it and I dont even want to read it. I feel like it treats me like a stupid machine."
    "Correcting my chat presentation: I used a labeled-field table with --- dividers when proposing the timestamp+restatement options. The psyche flagged this as noise. Dense inline prose is the discipline — for chat AND for markdown files."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:15:00Z)

(Decision
    "Timestamp in intent records is two positional fields, not one: a date field and a time field. Both bare-friendly in NOTA (the date is digits-and-hyphens; the time is digits-and-colon). The space between them is the NOTA positional separator, not a delimiter inside the value. Drops the T problem, drops the :00Z noise, and the visual reads as two clean fields."
    "why? that looks better. two fields, date then time."
    "Settling the timestamp shape: two positional fields (date, time). Insight that I'd missed — the space is the NOTA separator, not part of the value."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 18:30)

