(Decision
    "Verbatim-quoting convention for intent files and essence files. When a psyche statement is quoted directly (after speech-to-text correction), wrap it in markdown italics — `*verbatim text*` (single asterisks). The rest of the file is prose composed of intent-log summaries, written together as flowing prose describing the project's or workspace's intent. The italics denote 'this is the psyche's own words'; surrounding prose is the agent's synthesis (mostly unchanged summaries, sometimes composed into sentences). The same convention applies to ESSENCE.md and per-repo essence files."
    "if a verbatim psyche — if anything is verbatim from the psyche, from the psyche log, the verbatim log, then it should be in double asterisk surrounders. Or maybe something like that. I don't know. Maybe single asterisks or double asterisks. But we should use a standard like that. … whenever an intent is actually quoted directly from the psyche as the psyche said it, after speech-to-text correction, then it should be in some kind of asterisk surrounder or underline surrounder or something to denote that this is actually verbatim what the psyche said in his own words. And the rest is just prose of summaries written together as a straightforward file of intent."
    "Picked single asterisks (italics) — the psyche left between single / double / underline; italics is the lightest and renders cleanly in markdown. Documented in skills/intent-manifestation.md and cross-referenced from skills/repo-intent.md."
    Maximum
